Quoted By: >>30227483 >>30227655 >>30227858 >>30232434
>>30226935
I'm not sure why I'm still posting here, I pretty much never browse the thread anymore but this is an interesting question so I thought I'd try and figure it out
I don't know if you're still on but I went back and reread it (I read it a while back by deco's request) and figured it out.
from what I can figure out, the first, third, and fourth lines are the morse you can see on the voyager golden record's cover that detail how it should be played https://voyager.jpl.nasa.gov/golden-record/golden-record-cover/
you can see anon figuring that out on line 356 in the story. the first morse line is the timing for the video scan, as anon realizes, which is just binary for 8 (milliseconds). it's coded in binary with . (| on the record) = 1, and - = 0 and is set relative to a universal constant, the period of a hydrogen atom.
the third line is the record speed as anon deduces, 3.6 seconds/rotation, and is coded the same was as the first
the fourth is the running time of the record, one hour, coded the same way as the first and third lines
the second line however is just the number 1 in morse code

anon's realization is that the code sender is sending the instructions for playing the golden record that were printed on it not as any form of useful data, but to tell anon that's what it's doing - sending information about how to read what it's going to send next
and what it sends after that is -..---.. / --.----- / -...-.-. / --.----- / -...--.. / -..-.... / -..-...-
it uses the same system as on the golden record, . = 1, - = 0, and if you do that it translates to 01100011 00100000 01110101 00100000 01110011 01101111 01101110
which, if you plug into a binary to text translator, will give you "C U SON"
though it should be noted that in the story anon translates that as "C U SOON", so I'm guessing deco made a small oopsie and forgot an "O" in there

and that's it, there's the secret of the degeneracy pressure morse code which is actually binary
ez pz
